                <ol>

                  <li>
                    <b>Age of the Cooktop</b>
                    <ul>
                      <li>Typical Lifespan: Cooktops generally last between 10 to 20 years, depending on the brand, model, and how well they have been maintained.</li>
                      <li>Older Models: If your cooktop is nearing or has surpassed its typical lifespan, it might be more cost-effective to replace it rather than continuing to invest in repairs.</li>
                    </ul>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <b>Cost of Repairs vs. Replacement</b>
                    <ul>
                      <li>Repair Costs: Obtain a detailed estimate for the repair. If the repair cost is more than 50% of the price of a new cooktop, replacement might be the better option.</li>
                      <li>New Cooktop Costs: Compare the repair estimate with the cost of a new cooktop, including installation fees. Sometimes, the difference might not be substantial enough to justify repairing an old appliance.</li>
                    </ul>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <b>Frequency of Repairs</b>
                    <ul>
                      <li>Frequent Repairs: If you’ve had to repair the cooktop multiple times in the past few years, it may be more economical to replace it. Continuous repairs can quickly add up and become more expensive than purchasing a new unit.</li>
                      <li>First-Time Issue: If this is the first significant problem and the cooktop has otherwise been reliable, a repair might be the best course of action.</li>
                    </ul>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <b>Energy Efficiency</b>
                    <ul>
                      <li>Older Models: Older cooktops are typically less energy-efficient than newer models. Replacing an old cooktop with a modern, energy-efficient model can save you money on energy bills in the long term.</li>
                      <li>Environmental Impact: Energy-efficient appliances are better for the environment, reducing your carbon footprint.</li>
                    </ul>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <b>Availability of Parts</b>
                    <ul>
                      <li>Discontinued Models: If your cooktop model is discontinued and parts are hard to find or expensive, replacing the cooktop might be the more practical choice.</li>
                      <li>Readily Available Parts: If parts are easily available and not too costly, repairing the cooktop could be a straightforward solution.</li>
                    </ul>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <b>Technological Advancements</b>
                    <ul>
                      <li>New Features: Modern cooktops come with advanced features such as touch controls, induction heating, and enhanced safety features. If these advancements are important to you, upgrading to a new model might be worth considering.</li>
